My interest in Planning started right when I was a child, playing legos. I used to design small towns and explain to my parents the land use and road network pattern, though I didn't have a clue what land use was then. Then in my teens, I started playing computer games. One game that I was addicted to was Zoo Tycoon 2, where we had to build a zoo. It was pretty simple. Construct roads and create specific biomes for specific animals. The best thing I enjoyed in the game was creating road networks. I used to make loops of road network so that the people who used to come in can have a look at everything in one go. It was right then that I decided, I'd be choosing a course which allows me to construct cities. After my 12th, I decided to opt for Bachelors in Planning. And fortunately I've got into School of Planning and Architecture, Bhopal (SPAB).

First, when I joined SPAB, I was overwhelmed looking at all my friends. I thought I finally reached where I had to. In my first year, the course of Planning was pretty basic. In my third semester, we had Housing, we had to design a virtual township in a given area. What mostly interested me was in my fourth semester, when we had Transport Planning. We had been given a small area, and we had to conduct surveys, study about the traffic volume, analyze the road network, and come out with proposals. The part that I enjoyed in it was how we actually conduct surveys and analyze the data. And then finding out the gap and come out with necessary proposals. It all felt real. I had a feeling that I was working on the real world from then. During that semester, I unknowingly developed an interest in Transport Planning. Then I sat in our college library and started reading articles and books about Transport Planning. That made me more interested in Transport Planning. In two out of the three later semesters, I chose to stay in the group dealing with Transport issues. Ever since then I continuously gained knowledge on Transportation Planning.

In my current final semester, I've chosen "Planning for Pedestrians: Case of Charminar Precincts" as my thesis topic. Why did I choose this particular topic? One obvious reason would be my interest in Transport Planning. Second important reason was, every time I went to Charminar (a monumental old city area in Hyderabad), I abhorred the place. I find it very difficult to walk on the pavements, cross the streets and it is always crowded. Then I decided that I would be working on an issue related to ease the pedestrian movement in the Old City area.

I think a planner should have knowledge about the Planning policies and guidelines of different parts of the world. In my bachelors, we were taken to different parts of India as well as Bhutan. I gained immense knowledge about planning guidelines and policy making in these trips. I now think that I should pursue my masters outside India to improve my knowledge about planning in different countries. To add to it, my interest in Urban and Transport Planning and the way we can interlink them to make a city's ambience picture-perfect, forces me to opt for a course which has Urban Planning, and later I can specialize in Transport Planning

Ms Neha Naushad has managed to catch my attention with her tenacious commitment in her work during the time I was her faculty advisor and as her thesis coordinator. confidently, I can say that Neha Naushad is rated in the top 10% amongst the list of the students I had taught in my 13 years of teaching career with respect to research, analytical, critical thinking skills and social responsibility. | am writing this letter to give my highest possible recommendation to Ms NEHA NOWSHATH

Ms Neha Nowshath has managed to catch my attention with her tenacious commitment in her work during the time I was her thesis coordinator. Her thesis on  "Integrated Handloom Center in Trivandrum" aimed at re-establishing the importance of handloom industry and is a testament to her passion to help under represented and decaying artisan communities. The project was well thought out and the methodology was established early into the project development. The design process met with some initial hiccups but she recovered from it strong and fast, arriving at the most appropriate design solution possible. During her 6 month internship at the largest NGO in shelter making - Habitat , her mentor architect G.Shankar gave positive feedback on her professionalism and eagerness to learn.

As the faculty advisor of her batch, I could observe Ms  Neha Nowshath was a student with consistent academic records, interested both in academic and extracurricular activities.  She was the class representative for  the Student's  Affairs Council (SAC) during her 4th and 5th year . She has also represented the department in various inter-university events such as  Zonal NASA 2017 (shortlisted for convention trophy) and NASA 2017 ( shortlisted for ANDC Trophy).

Neha is sincere and capable of handling responsibilities efficiently. Excellent communication, listening, organizational, problem-solving and time-management skills made her capable of leading the architecture students association as their creative head in 2016.

Her perseverance to do the assigned work also enabled her to successfully play the roles of junior executive, senior executive, and event manager during successive editions of Ragam (University cultural festival) . She also worked as the creative head of the Dance and Dramatics club and as an illustrator for the college magazine (3rd year).

I can confidently say that Neha Nowshath is rated in the top 10% amongst the list of the students I had taught in my 13 years of teaching career with respect to research, analytical, critical thinking skills and social responsibility. Considering these facts, I strongly support her candidature for Master’s course at your esteemed institute. I also recommend her for any scholarships/fellowships at your university, if it is available. Kindly contact me for any additional information in support of this deserving candidate.

Some of the most defining years of my intellectual growth were my 5 years of undergraduate study. I stayed at the institute hostel with students form varied branches of study and was also a part of many social clubs in the campus. Many of our evenings were spent hanging out at the common hall or dining room discussing and debating a myriad of subjects. This not only made me a more tolerating and a humble human being, but also helped me forge some strong friendship with people from across the country. This also helped me get through some very tough times during my education.

When I received the email invitation to apply for the Atkinson Tetreault Scholarship what caught my attention apart from the exciting monetary benefits (which will ease my large student loan burden) was the prospect of sharing a roof with many other individuals of different expertise and background. The opportunity to meet many people from across the world and listen to their stories is not something that I have had the luxury to do so far. Also, it will help to be a part of a strong knit community that will look after each other during all times.

I believe, with my strong cultural background, a steady academic growth and the desire to learn and grow together will make me a good addition to the Telluride family. I am not a person to shy away from my responsibilities and so, I will enthusiastically take part in my commitments to the house. I am also no stranger to community living and hence, I imagine it will not be difficult to become a part of such an environment. This opportunity to be a part of Telluride will give my time at Cornell much more meaning than just attaining a graduate degree.

Globalization is a much debated topic among academicians

As kids we are easily impressionable. Some incidents leave their marks in us. One such incident in my life was witnessing a death. Even though I spent most of the year in the lush green state of Kerala, my summer vacations were spent playing at the dry streets of a small town Nagercoil in Tamil Nadu. The difference in the surrounding was stark. In Kerala, there were more trees than I could count whereas in Nagercoil, there was a single tree on the entire street- a large Gulmohar tree. I usually went there during the month of March and the tree would be at full bloom during this month. Its blood red flowers with yellow accents mimicked the colors of fire and so fittingly earned the name – fire of the forest. It was a majestic tree. But one fine morning I woke up to loud cutting noises. That day I witnessed the death of a tree. To this day I do not know the reason for cutting it down and nothing was replanted at its spot. What did change was my awareness of the presence of a Gulmohar tree anywhere I travelled to. There were many Gulmohars on the sides of the road occasionally bursting into brilliant shades of red. But over time these were all cut down for development purposes and were replaced with faster growing trees for landscaping. One may not find anything wrong as a tree is replaced with another tree but the value that is cut down is not accounted for. Many such indigenous trees meet this cruel end. The centuries of stories they hold is lost with a few blows of the axe.

Even in Kerala, I grew up near a Tamil community. The streets are lines with traditional tamil houses with sloping roofs and small windows. The front yard of these houses is the common street which is used for multiple purposes. One of the most peculiar uses is to dry grains, pulses and red chilly in the sun. Large straw mats are unrolled onto the mud ground and multitudes of ingredients were dried in the sun to be later used for cooking purposes. In the evening, everything is sorted and collected in large tins and stored for seasons ahead. One main benefiter of this practice is the common sparrow. They find the roofs of the traditional houses an ideal nesting space as it is shady and small enough to protect them from larger predators. They also find enough and more food for sustenance by relying on the grains and pulses left behind after the drying process. The temple well served as their water resource. I used to always see a large group of sparrows pecking around in the late evening un-amused by the happenings around. This was 10 years back. Today when I walk through the streets, I neither see any sparrows nor any women drying grains. The narrow traditional houses have disappeared too.

I discussed these changes with my neighbors and friends and they did not notice it until I pointed it out to them. That made me realize how ignorant we could be about such changes we classify as insignificant. They may not be important issues in the immediate scenario but on the long run, these could prove disastrous if not resolved. When we think about disadvantages of globalization, we emphasize on generalized trade, decline of local economies, environmental decline and the like. But the cultural value and significance that is being lost is rarely being accounted for.

26/09/2019.message: Meow
Meow
Yesterday I was working  in the middle of night in an empty office
The Watchman came and switched off every light but one,
He was walking around and then walking away, away from the only light, to the  door , a guardian, a silent protecter
If I squint I could see  that cape on him
His head held upright ,over his frail body .
in the darkness his oily hair shined  ,
Even his cape would have oil ...I think
But he was looking at me
I could see his eyes lingering on and away
That single light, it bothered him , he is used to the darkness , he wants it off
Maybe it was his ocd ,
but do poor people have ocd ??
Isn't that a too rich a desease for him?
Or maybe he just want me to go home
He wants me to meet a girl , kiss her goodnight before we sleep
Maybe there is wisdom in his thought
He has sat there for ages , have watched my bosses come and go ,
He has seen their hailines receding and guts bulging
He had seen their eyes , once when it had passion
He may have looked into them today morning and seen a stranger
I sat there in the spotlight as his next specimen
But that's not me , I have a plan , I am going to travel,
I'm not having a Marriage or baby anytime soon
I'm single, a bachelor , the world is out there to grab
This is just temporary, Reviews are coming in next meeting and I just want to be on the safe side
Maybe I could start the gym again ...
I have definitely gained some, but well It's ok
I have good clothes, a car , a stunning vest and many ties.
I've gotten more attention from ladies than I did 5 years ago...I was in much better shape back then
But then why ??
Am I the safe bet guy ??
Am I that guy?  ...with a job, good enough savings , with a decent car and a show off watch ??
Damm it ...I need a walk
I get up .... I could feel buttons trying to push back my stomach which was spilling over my belt
And I could feel him out there watching ..  judging in the dark
No, that's enough , I get it ...I have changed ,but such is life,
things change , I can't hold on to the past
And this doesn't mean I can't go back ... I'm just trying not to upset anybody ... I am just to scared to upset them , they have always looked up to me
I have always been scared, I am scared to step outside this circle of light that surrounds me ...
Mom told me there are deamons in the dark
Vissious creatures big uncertainty
But here it is warm , there isn't much... but it's warm and I know what comes at me ...but it's scary out there isn't it ??
I need to leave ...
I packed my bag
I switched off the light , I looked at him , ...happy now ??
I walked out closing the door behind slowly
Without waking the guard ,
...it's ok you sleep now ,it's been a long day
It's not really that scary out there .... right??..
